snippet.textDisplay: In Google's defense, they aren't listening to you for the sake of being curious about what you are saying but rather your recording is processed for training voice recognition. While yes, they have the recording, and yes, you can identify people with some of them (obviously) they aren't public, aren't used for identifying people, and aren't intended for anything but training speech recognition. How else should they train? The part that they did wrong is doing it by default and not on an "opt-in" basis. Saying "we will use your recordings for training if you use google assistant" in the fine print is not a valid excuse. It should ask "can we use your recordings for training?" when using it. This is something you can still configure by the way, but you have to opt-out.
